    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-10-14T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-10-14T17:00:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.61334/139: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bading</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-14T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1924—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. Your 15, October 7, 3 p.m. You should discuss this matter again earnestly
                    with the President at the earliest opportunity, stating that the Department
                    relies on the assurances given by ex-President Tamayo, who in his letter of
                    February 5, 1922, to Minister Hartman<note n="11" xml:id="d645fn11">Not
                        printed.</note> declared that if in 1925 the credit of the Mercantile Bank
                    of the Americas has not been extinguished the tax will be extended until its
                    cancellation.</p>
                <p>You should impress upon the President the importance which the Department
                    attaches to the matter and reiterate that the Department relies on his
                    assurances mentioned in your 14, September 22, 4 p.m. and that the Department
                    therefore confidently expects that he will use his influence to have a law
                    passed extending the tax until the debt is paid.</p>
                <p>You may also point out the decidedly adverse effect upon the credit of Ecuador,
                    should it fail to provide for the payment of its debts, as was recognized by
                    President Tamayo in his letter above referred to.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
